               <p>JOHN ABBOTT. I am in partnership with four other persons, who <rs id="t18300415-361-viclabel1953" type="occupation">keep the <placeName id="t18300415-361-crimeloc1954">City of London tavern</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-361-crimeloc1954" type="placeName" value="City of London tavern"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-361-crimeloc1954" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-361-off1951 t18300415-361-crimeloc1954"></join>
                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-361-victim2984 t18300415-361-viclabel1953"></join>: the prisoner was our <rs id="t18300415-361-deflabel1955" type="occupation">apprentice</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-361-defend2982 t18300415-361-deflabel1955"></join>. On the 29th of March we missed a fork and a spoon, and on the 30th I found the prisoner in the passage with one of our porters - he pretended to be fainting, and the fork fell from his jacket; I told the porter to feel up his trousers, and he felt the spoon - I sent him into the hall, and the porter said there had been a man with him in the street; I said, "Come to the door, and point him out to me;" he went and said, "That is the man;" I sent for him - he came in, and I asked him to write his address down; he wrote his mother's address, and said his father was electioneering - I took the prisoner to the Mansion-house; he said he was going to pawn these articles to pay his brother 2s.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-361-person2985">
                  CHARLES 
                  KNIGHT
               <interp inst="t18300415-361-person2985" type="surname" value="KNIGHT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-361-person2985" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-361-person2985" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a porter at the tavern. On the 30th of March, between six and seven o'clock in the morning, my fellow-servant in the kitchen told me he saw a spoon and a fork behind the dresser; I said, "We will not take them away till we see who goes out;" and the first that went out was the prisoner - then we looked, and saw they were removed; I went, and found the prisoner in the street, and brought him back - the fork dropped from him in the passage, and I found the spoon up his trousers.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I did not take them with intent to steal them.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300415-361-verdict1956" type="verdictDescription">
